Introduction

Given a set of gene expression data, we want to run an unsupervised clustering. This dataset consists of gene expression profiles across multiple samples. Each row represents a specific gene, identified by its unique gene_name, while each column (P1 through P1028) represents expression levels in different patient samples or experimental conditions.

Workflow

  1. Determine Optimal Clusters (K): Use Mercator to generate a Scree plot and an Auer-Gervini plot to identify the best number of clusters (K) for the dataset.
  2. Evaluate Distance Metrics: Perform hierarchical clustering using the identified K value and compare three distance measures (Euclidean, Manhattan, and Canberra) by computing silhouette width to determine the optimal approach.
  3. Visualize Clustering Results: Apply UMAP and t-SNE to visualize the clustering, ensuring that data points are color-coded by Cluster ID for better interpretability.

Generating Binary Matrix

The Mercator package primarily operates on a BinaryMatrix S4 object, which serves as input for various functions and visualizations. While originally designed for binary data, BinaryMatrix can also handle integer and numeric values. Additionally, Mercator’s visualization tools support arbitrary distance matrices, enhancing its flexibility for data analysis.[Abrams and colleages]

df_copy <- as.matrix(df_copy[,-1])
my.binmat <- BinaryMatrix(df_copy)
summary(my.binmat)
## An object of the 'BinaryMatrix' class, of size
## [1]  431 1028
## History:
## [1] "Newly created."

Hierarchical clustering

Euclidean distance

euc.vis <- Mercator(my.binmat, "euclid", "hclust", 22)
plot(euc.vis, view = "hclust")

Silhouette-Width Barplot

barplot(euc.vis)

Manhattan Distance

mhatt.vis <- Mercator(my.binmat, "manhattan", "hclust", 22)
plot(mhatt.vis, view = "hclust")

Silhouette-Width Barplot

barplot(mhatt.vis)

Canberra Distance

canb.vis <- Mercator(my.binmat, "canberra", "hclust", 22)
plot(canb.vis, view = "hclust")

Silhouette-Width Barplot

barplot(canb.vis)

UMAP plot (supposing its manhattan)

mhatt.vis <- addVisualization(mhatt.vis, "umap")
plot(mhatt.vis, view = "umap", main="UMAP; Manhattan Distance")

TSNE plot

mhatt.vis <- addVisualization(mhatt.vis, "tsne", perplexity=25)
plot(mhatt.vis, view = "tsne", main="t-SNE; Manhattan Distance")

Discussion

Our Scree plot gave more clearer cutoff at 22 clusters hence we used the optimal clusters as 22. We therefore run hierarchical clustering using Euclidean, Manhattan and Canberra distance metrics. We compare their Mean Silhoutte width below.

Distance metric Mean SW
Euclidean 0.28731
Manhattan 0.35059
Canberra 0.1076

The Best distance metric from our analysis was Manhattan distance. Hence shown in the UMAP and TSNE plots. In the UMAP visualization, the points are spread along a continuous trajectory, with clusters loosely connected, highlighting a balance between global structure and local relationships. This layout suggests that UMAP retains some meaningful relationships across the dataset as a whole. On the other hand, the t-SNE visualization shows well-separated, distinct clusters with no apparent connections between them, emphasizing the local structure of the data. While t-SNE excels at creating compact and visually distinct groups, it does so at the expense of global structure, as distances between clusters may not carry significant meaning. Both figures offer complementary perspectives, with UMAP showcasing broader dataset patterns and t-SNE emphasizing finer, local groupings.
